SIMPLE: header
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Header
<hw>Head"er</hw> <pr>(h⟦ecr⟧d"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>One who, or that which, heads nails, rivets, etc., esp. a machine
for heading.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who heads a movement, a party, or a mob; head;
chief; leader.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A brick or stone
laid with its shorter face or head in the surface of the wall.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>In framing, the piece of timber fitted between two
trimmers, and supported by them, and carrying the ends of the
tailpieces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A reaper for wheat, that cuts off the heads
only.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A fall or plunge head first, as while riding a
bicycle, or a skateboard, or in bathing; -- sometimes, implying the
striking of the head on the ground; <as>as, to take a
<ex>header</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Headforemost</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Headfirst</ent>⟦br⟧
